Alright, so with i3 there isnâ€™t a â€œdesktop environment daemonâ€ to hold your hand â€” youâ€™ve got to set up Bluetooth the *right* way. Let me break it down: ^ref-5e408692-1-0

---

## 1. Make sure the base Bluetooth stack is installed

On Ubuntu/Debian: ^ref-5e408692-7-0

```bash
sudo apt install bluez blueman pulseaudio-module-bluetooth
```

* `bluez` â†’ the Linux Bluetooth stack.
* `blueman` â†’ GTK manager for pairing (nice tray app, works well with i3). ^ref-5e408692-14-0
* `pulseaudio-module-bluetooth` (or `pipewire-pulse` if youâ€™re on PipeWire) â†’ lets audio devices work. ^ref-5e408692-15-0

---

## 2. Enable the Bluetooth service

Check the systemd service: ^ref-5e408692-21-0

```bash
systemctl status bluetooth
```

If itâ€™s not running: ^ref-5e408692-27-0

```bash
sudo systemctl enable --now bluetooth
```

---

## 3. Pick how you want to interact

Youâ€™ve got choices here: ^ref-5e408692-37-0

* **Terminal only (bare metal):**

  ```bash
  bluetoothctl
  ```

  Inside: ^ref-5e408692-45-0

  ```
  power on
  agent on
  default-agent
  scan on
  pair <MAC>
  connect <MAC>
  trust <MAC>
  ```

* **With GUI helper (nicer in i3):** ^ref-5e408692-57-0
  Launch `blueman-applet` in the background â€” it gives you a systray icon.
  Add this line to your `~/.config/i3/config`:

  ```

  ```
^ref-5e408692-61-0
 ^ref-5e408692-65-0
  (You need a systray bar module like `i3status-rs` / `polybar` / `i3bar` with `tray_output` enabled.)

---

## 4. Audio-specific (Pulse/PipeWire)

After connecting, sometimes the profile defaults to â€œheadsetâ€ instead of â€œA2DPâ€. You can fix it:

* GUI: `pavucontrol` â†’ Output Devices â†’ switch profile to A2DP. ^ref-5e408692-74-0
* CLI:

  ```bash
  pactl list cards short
  pactl set-card-profile <card#> a2dp_sink
  ```

---

## 5. Useful shortcuts in i3
 ^ref-5e408692-85-0
Add to `~/.config/i3/config` for quick toggling:
 ^ref-5e408692-87-0
```i3

^ref-5e408692-87-0
```
